[2] Cholera - India (New Delhi)
Date: Wed 27 Sep 2008
Source: The Times of India [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Delhi/Post-floods_cholera_cases_rise_in_Capital/articleshow/3532051.cms>


Cases of cholera reported in September [2008] have gone up due to
increased contamination of drinking water after floods in the Yamuna,
according to the Municipal Corporation of Delhi (MCD). Until 22 Sep
2008, 136 cases of cholera have been reported as compared to 106
cases reported in 2007 in September.

Moreover, leader of the opposition J K Sharma has alleged that
chlorine tablets being distributed by the civic agency were beyond
their expiry date. Said chairman medical relief and public health
committee: "Cases of cholera have increased this month [September
2008] due to contamination of drinking water due to floods in the
Yamuna. In 2007, a total of 1213 cases of cholera were reported as
compared to 732 cases until 22 Sep 2008."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of actual cases appears to be in dispute but both sides
agree that it has increased over the same period in 2007.

A map of India showing New Delhi, in the north, can be found at
<http://www.nationsonline.org/bilder/map_of_india50.jpg> - Mod.LL]

